**Movie Recommendation Engine**

This project implements a Movie Recommendation Engine using various techniques like Collaborative Filtering, Content-Based Filtering, and a Hybrid Approach. The engine suggests relevant movies to a given user based on their preferences.

**Problem Statement**

Build a recommendation engine that suggests relevant movies to a user based on their past preferences.

**Dataset**

The dataset used is the **MovieLens dataset**, which consists of the following files:

\- Movies (\`movies.csv\`): Contains movie information like movieId, title, genres.  
\- Links (\`links.csv\`): Provides identifiers for \`movieId\` such as \`imdbId\`, \`tmdbId\`.  
\- Tags (\`tags.csv\`): User-generated tags information (\`userId\`, \`movieId\`, \`tag\`, \`timestamp\`).  
\- Ratings (\`ratings.csv\`): User ratings data (\`userId\`, \`movieId\`, \`rating\`, \`timestamp\`).  
\- Tag Genome (\`genome-scores.csv\`, \`genome-tags.csv\`): Tags and their relevance scores.

**Data Insights**

\- The dataset contains 58,098 unique movies and 283,228 unique users.  
\- 78 movieIds have duplicate titles.  
\- 13,176 movies are associated with genome tags.  
\- There are 1,128 genome tags in the dataset.  
\- 53,889 movies have been rated by users.  
\- 45,981 user-generated unique tags are associated with the movies.

**Model Selection**

Three distinct methods are employed: **Content-Based Filtering (CBF)**, **Collaborative Filtering (CF)**, and **Singular Value Decomposition (SVD)**. Ultimately, a hybrid recommendation engine is developed, combining the outputs of all three techniques to determine the most suitable movie for the user.

***High level architecture***  
**![][image5]**

***Content-Based Filtering (CBF)***

***Title-Based Content Filtering***

Used TF-IDF and Cosine Similarity to build the content-based filtering model:

\- Input: Movie title  
\- Output: Most similar movies  
\- Cosine similarity is computed using a matrix of TF-IDF vectors for all movies

***User-Based Content Filtering***

\- Input: \`UserId\`  
\- Output: Most relevant movies for the user.  
\- Cosine similarity between the user’s document profile and item profile.

***Collaborative Filtering (KNN-based)***

Applied K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) for collaborative filtering:

\- Input: \`UserId\`, number of movies  
\- Output: Top \`n\` movies based on the user’s preferences.  
\- Used K-Fold Cross Validation to estimate ratings.

***Matrix Factorization (SVD)***

Used Singular Value Decomposition (SVD) to recommend movies:

\- Input: \`UserId\`, number of movies  
\- Output: Top \`n\` movies based on the user’s preferences.  
  

**Results**

**Content-Based Filtering (CBF)**  
\- Recommended movies based on the user’s content preferences. (Based on max similarity)

**Collaborative Filtering (KNN)**  
\- Results: RMSE: 0.8018, MAE: 0.6035.

**Matrix Factorization (SVD)**  
\- Results: RMSE: 0.7997, MAE: 0.6025.

**Hybrid Recommendation Engine**

The hybrid system combines SVD and CBF to provide:

\- Top 20 movie recommendations based on user preferences.  
\- Top 10 movies with the most similar content/genres to what the user prefers.

**Future Improvements**

\- Use web scraping to gather more accurate user preferences for new users.  
\- Gather more metadata using \`imdbId\` and \`tmdbId\`.  
\- Enhance recommendations by incorporating demographic and regional data.

**Conclusion**

This project demonstrates how Content-Based Filtering, Collaborative Filtering, and Matrix Factorization can be used to build a recommendation engine. Future work can further improve recommendations using additional metadata and user-specific information.
